data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The workaround you configured in .NET 10 no longer exists.

Every synchronous LINQ call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime because the Cosmos SDK is inherently async-only.

### Fix: migrate to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key steps:**
1. Replace all sync LINQ terminators with their `*Async` counterparts
2. Make methods `async Task<T>` (or `async Task` for void)
3. `await` every async call
4. Propagate `async` up the call chain (controllers, services, etc.)
5. Remove the old sync-over-async opt-in config — it's a no-op now

`Add()` remains synchronous (it's an in-memory tracking call, not a DB operation). The actual I/O happens at `SaveChangesAsync()`.
